Can't recommend it at all. Indoor dining went way over the allowed 50% capacity, not to mention the outdoor space which was super crowded. The tables were ridiculously small and it was impossible to sit there comfortably. The music was super loud, we couldn't keep up a conversation as we couldn't hear each other. Out waiter was absolutely terrible: he spilled my cocktail all over the place, to the floor and onto the table then spilled the fries as well to my husbands lap an on the floor--it hasn't even crossed his mind to replace the fries with a new one given that the 1/3 of it ended on the floor. The food is mediocre, the burger patty was chewy. The cocktail was awful: it should've been a mix of different drinks (hence the name and according to what was on the menu) but I only could taste the very strong, cheap booze. Delicious, well executed food dishes. We had a reservation and were sat immediately. Tables were closer together than I am comfortable with however. Started with the prosciutto app and the burrata and rosemary focaccia were delicious. We also tried the squid ink croquettes pictured below and were blown away. For entrees, I did the lobster risotto special and he did the pappardelle bolognese. The 2nd best bolognese I have ever tried, the flavor was excellent. Dessert was good, but I wish there was a more diverse selection. No chocolate for valentines day was odd. My cocktail was delicious and strong, though small for the price, and there isn't a ton of diversity on the cocktail menu. Staff here was lovely. And the place smelled incredible with the scents from the kitchen wafting out.  We will be back so I can try the crab pasta dish.

My girlfriend and I went here for Valentine's day. The outdoor heaters worked very well, and the entire staff that waited on us were extremely friendly. Our server, Antonio was a particular pleasure and was extremely attentive to our needs. This food was nothing short of absolutely amazing. We started with the calamari and risotto croquettes. The croquettes were extremely well made and the calamari was tender and very fresh. For entree we had the gnocchi carbonara and pappardelle bolognese. Nothing was too rich or filling and portioned perfectly. Everything tasted absolutely phenomenal. All the flavors were in perfect balance and I am currently craving more. We shared a tiramisu to end the night which was the best way we could have imagined finishing. The corkage fee was also more than reasonable. Have a meal here as soon as you can! You will remember it for a long time to come guaranteed!

Honestly, one of the best dining experiences I’ve had in New York. The service was top notch and the food was excellent. The octopus was some of the best I’ve ever had and I loved the cacio e pepe, lobster pasta, and all of the desserts we ordered (tiramisu, date cake, and afogato gelato). The heated outdoor seating area was much warmer than other spots I’ve been to and sectioned off well (we sat in the area in front of the restaurant). Looking forward to returning often and definitely some of the best Italian food I’ve had in NY.

Reliably excellent food and service, with a frequently updated menu that nevertheless leaves a space for the classics. Paccheri, gnocci, tagliatelle, meatballs, and octopus aww stand-outs. Beautiful indoor space plus a beautiful roofed garden covered in ivy. A place you will find yourself coming back to, both fir an everyday meal and special events.

The name alone drew me into this place. Beautiful restaurant. They have a small menu but the items I had were tasty. I ordered the Parpadelle Bolognese with a Blood Orange  Soda. Both were quite delicious.  The plates are small, not like your usual Italian Eatery. I wouldn't recommend for children being that it's a small seasonal menu and unless your child has an open palette, they may not understand what they're ordering. My kids had no idea what was on the menu and didn't care for what they ordered, so after we finished up, I bought them pizza from a pizzeria. The food is fairly priced. Ranging from about $19 to $30. I was told in order to sing happy birthday and cut a cake that my mother brought, it would cost us $3 per person, which was a downside to this pretty place. I didn't understand why, it's just a small bday cake but I guess everyone has their own rules. I was fine with cutting it at home, no big deal.

The food was good but expensive. I can't believe that I bought a cake to sing Happy Birthday to my daughter and they told me if I cut my daughter a cake I would have to pay an extra 18.00. I spend 150.20 you would think with the money I spent is ok to cut a small Birthday cake but I was wrong so we ended cutting the cake at home. I was so disappointed that I will never go to that restaurant again.

Second, the backyard was packed, all the tables were so close together and weren’t spaced enough 6ft apart. They just want to fit a lot of customers and don’t care about others health. My friend suggested we do Aurora for brunch on Sunday, so we made a reservation via OpenTable and headed over. Making a reservation was super easy and quick! We were able to be seated in their outdoor patio right when we arrived which was great. The patio is gorgeous and the whole place really has a straight out of Italy vibe to it.  The ambience was very lax and this is a great place to have a date or go to brunch with friends. The food is superb! We started out with the pancetta appetizer. Which was great, however our service experience was not so great. It took our waiter almost 15 mins to acknowledge us. Once he finally did we decided that we would order everything at once to avoid the wait. Our appetizer arrived 20 mins later and at that point we didn’t even have drinks- just the Lukewarm tap water. We waited over an hour for our main courses- to the point where our Waiter, who I believe his name was William(listed on receipt) asked us if we were Interested in dessert????? I was extremely disappointed because had he checked in on our table he would have realized we hadn’t been served in over an hour- no drink refills-nothing.  Out of frustration , we spoke to the manager Stefano who was very courteous and made sure we were taken care of for the rest of our time there. However our waiter never apologized nor did he make an effort to try to mend the experience for us.  Aurora Management- you guys have a beautiful establishment, please hire people that will take care of your customers properly so they’re able to enjoy their experience there. Not sure if I will be coming back, again everything was great aside from the service.

From the second we walked in, the hostess was incredibly rude. We came as a walk-in two top on a Friday night and were told there were no tables available (we live in the neighborhood, we knew to expect a wait) but the hostess was talking to us like we were ridiculous for even asking. I ask the wait time, it’s a measly 30 minutes so I give her my number and we grab a drink next door while we wait for the call.  40 minutes later, we get the call that our “outdoor table is ready”. I excitedly tell her that we’ll be there in 2 minutes. When we arrive, she has given our table away and we’re sat indoors at the most hectic table in the house, at the crossroads of the service bar, the doorway to the patio, and the bread cutting station. The hostess told us they were out of menus and that we would get some in a minute, meanwhile she sits another table in front of us and gives them menus immediately.  We finally get our menus and some bread with olive oil (great bread, inedible oil — and I love olive oil). We then ordered the octopus to start, which was fine but under seasoned.  Then we waited. And waited. And waited for our pasta. Other tables had come and gone and we still had not been served our dinner. We ordered two pastas from the main menu and it took an hour to get to us. One of our servers (of which we had several, but still were very underserved) apologized an hour into our wait and offered to comp us a glass of wine, we went with dessert instead. When our pasta finally arrived, it was chewy and under cooked.  I’ve been wanting to eat at Aurora for a long time and I’ve never been so disappointed. I thought it was hard to ruin Italian food but I was sadly proven wrong. No one talked to us, no one checked in with us. Everyone ran around the restaurant like chickens with their heads cut off and despite the beautiful decor, it was a very stressful and disappointing dinner.

1st Aurora came with high recommendation from a local professional contact 2nd the appetizer soup was good, and the atmosphere was nice enough. BUT after 25 minutes between the soup and entree & 20 minutes since the last waiter check-in, I waved over a manager to inquire about our food. He came back promptly and said it would be right out. At the 30 minutes post-soup, the entrees had still not arrived, and the tables next to us (seated after us) had gone through 2-3 courses. So I waved over our long-lost waiter. This is where it got strange... I was explaining calmly about the food when the waiter jerked his shoulder back and gave a defensive look. I'd touched his shoulder gently as I was talking with my hands... I'd obviously crossed a boundary of some sort.  I apologized and continued my story. So, he had another manager come over and the food appeared just after... Now we were about 35 minutes post appetizer soup. The manager was friendly and offered the food for free... But we were so frustrated that we departed, declining an offer of free to-go.  Paid the bill, minus the entrees, and left... We weren't looking for free food, and we'd felt neglected, disrespected and invisible. To eat the food would have created more discontent at this point.  Most importantly, we're left wondering why the waiter didn't check in on us or why nobody noticed us sitting there for so long with an  empty table??? ... And I'm perplexed by the waiter's body language, recoiling at a friendly touch while a guest is asking for help... I've never experienced that from anybody, and BTW I'm not particularly a touchy guy. 🤔 It all started out pleasant enough, and we were literally the 2nd table seated for the dinner seatings.

The three best spots for Italian in Williamsburg are Lilia, Antica Pesa and Aurora. The best food for your buck, with a low key ambiance (the patio is beautiful) that doesn't require a reservation over a month in advance is Aurora.The burrata and pastas are delish, love the pork chop too. Haven't tried brunch yet, but would go for dinner any night of the week!

EDIT: This has become one of my favorite restaurants. Over the last year I've been here at least 7-8 times - mostly for dinner but twice for brunch. The food is always great. The menu often changes to stay original. Definitely a bonus is their commitment to use fresh and organic ingredients. Atmosphere is awesome and the service is always professional.
